The paper deals with the complexity of graph problems, specifically sparse graph problems. This suggests that it could belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also introduces new conditional hardness conjectures and proposes a new notion of sparse reductions, which could place it in the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. The use of graph theory and algorithms to solve these problems could also suggest the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with the computation of shortest paths and cycles, which could place it in the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the complexity of computing dominating sets, which could suggest the cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-category.
